1
00:01:08,403 --> 00:01:12,760
<i>You will travel far, my little Kal-El.</i>

2
00:01:13,323 --> 00:01:15,393
<i>But we will never leave you...</i>

3
00:01:15,803 --> 00:01:18,363
<i>...even in the face of our deaths.</i>

4
00:01:19,563 --> 00:01:21,997
<i>You will make my strength your own.</i>

5
00:01:23,283 --> 00:01:26,434
<i>You will see my life through your eyes...</i>

6
00:01:27,363 --> 00:01:30,002
<i>...as your life will be seen through mine.</i>

7
00:01:31,283 --> 00:01:37,199
<i>The son becomes the father,</i>
<i>and the father the son.</i>

8
00:04:54,363 --> 00:04:56,797
<i>In spite of your past...</i>

9
00:04:58,963 --> 00:05:01,557
...I know you're a good man.

10
00:05:03,003 --> 00:05:04,721
And all good men...

11
00:05:05,243 --> 00:05:07,632
...deserve a second chance.

12
00:05:15,363 --> 00:05:18,321
From the moment
I received your first letter...

13
00:05:18,483 --> 00:05:21,202
...I knew you were not like the rest.

14
00:05:22,683 --> 00:05:26,437
You came from nothing...

15
00:05:27,043 --> 00:05:29,762
...and you worked so hard
to get where you are.

16
00:05:30,683 --> 00:05:33,402
You might have made a few mistakes.

17
00:05:33,763 --> 00:05:36,436
- Gertrude, for God's sake!
- Damn it, Gertrude, let us in now!

18
00:05:36,803 --> 00:05:42,002
You said that if I helped you
get out of prison...

19
00:05:43,083 --> 00:05:45,517
...you'd take care of me.

20
00:05:46,483 --> 00:05:48,553
And you have.

21
00:05:49,883 --> 00:05:53,922
You've shown me pleasures
that I've never known.

22
00:05:55,563 --> 00:05:57,679
That's why you deserve...

23
00:05:57,843 --> 00:05:59,674
...everything.

24
00:06:03,003 --> 00:06:04,436
I love you...

25
00:06:04,963 --> 00:06:06,919
...Lex Luthor.

26
00:06:22,483 --> 00:06:24,872
Gertrude, let us in. He's a crook.

27
00:06:25,043 --> 00:06:26,999
He doesn't love you, Gertrude!

28
00:06:27,163 --> 00:06:28,482
He's a monster! Gertrude!

29
00:06:45,403 --> 00:06:47,519
- You can keep that.
- Oh, God.

30
00:06:47,683 --> 00:06:48,911
The rest is mine.

31
00:06:55,083 --> 00:06:56,721
We're done.

32
00:07:25,043 --> 00:07:27,113
Bye, Martha.

33
00:09:57,523 --> 00:09:59,514
Oh, Clark.

34
00:10:02,323 --> 00:10:05,042
Oh, my boy.

35
00:10:51,123 --> 00:10:53,683
Will you get that thing out of my face!

36
00:11:00,003 --> 00:11:01,994
Lex, your friends give me the creeps.

37
00:11:02,163 --> 00:11:03,960
Prison is a creepy place, Kitty.

38
00:11:04,123 --> 00:11:06,478
One needs to make creepy friends
in order to survive.

39
00:11:06,643 --> 00:11:09,032
Even a man with my vast talents
is worth less inside...

40
00:11:09,203 --> 00:11:12,912
...than a carton of cigarettes and
a sharp piece of metal in your pocket.

41
00:11:16,443 --> 00:11:19,480
Do you know the story of Prometheus?
No, of course you don't.

42
00:11:19,643 --> 00:11:23,522
Prometheus was a god who stole
the power of fire from the other gods...

43
00:11:23,683 --> 00:11:25,355
...and gave control of it to mortals.

44
00:11:25,523 --> 00:11:28,083
In essence, he gave us technology.
He gave us power.

45
00:11:28,243 --> 00:11:31,633
So we're stealing fire? In the Arctic.

46
00:11:31,803 --> 00:11:35,273
Actually, sort of. You see, whoever
controls technology controls the world.

47
00:11:35,443 --> 00:11:38,003
The Roman Empire ruled the world
because they built roads.

48
00:11:38,163 --> 00:11:40,996
The British Empire ruled the world
because they built ships.

49
00:11:41,163 --> 00:11:44,519
America, the atom bomb,
and so on and so forth.

50
00:11:44,683 --> 00:11:46,275
I just want what Prometheus wanted.

51
00:11:46,643 --> 00:11:50,113
Sounds great, Lex, but you're not a god.

52
00:11:53,043 --> 00:11:55,955
Gods are selfish beings
who fly around in little red capes...

53
00:11:56,123 --> 00:11:58,318
...and don't share their power
with mankind.

54
00:11:58,483 --> 00:12:00,041
Hey, boss.

55
00:12:00,643 --> 00:12:02,201
We found something.

56
00:12:06,923 --> 00:12:09,517
No, I don't wanna be a god.

57
00:12:09,683 --> 00:12:12,641
I just wanna bring fire to the people.

58
00:12:13,683 --> 00:12:17,198
And I want my cut.

59
00:12:58,163 --> 00:13:00,393
Was this his house?

60
00:13:01,163 --> 00:13:03,631
You might think so. Most would.

61
00:13:03,803 --> 00:13:06,715
This is more of a monument
to a long dead...

62
00:13:06,883 --> 00:13:09,351
...and extremely powerful civilization.

63
00:13:09,523 --> 00:13:12,083
This is where he learned who he was.

64
00:13:12,563 --> 00:13:15,123
This is where he came for guidance.

65
00:13:25,603 --> 00:13:27,559
Possibilities.

66
00:13:27,723 --> 00:13:31,636
Endless possibilities.

67
00:14:14,763 --> 00:14:17,641
You act like you've been here before.

68
00:14:42,643 --> 00:14:44,395
<i>My son...</i>

69
00:14:46,803 --> 00:14:49,112
<i>...you do not remember me.</i>

70
00:14:50,043 --> 00:14:52,079
<i>I am Jor-El.</i>

71
00:14:52,483 --> 00:14:54,474
<i>I'm your father.</i>

72
00:14:54,643 --> 00:14:58,556
<i>By now, I will have been dead</i>
<i>many thousands of your years.</i>

73
00:14:58,723 --> 00:15:02,079
- He thinks I'm his son.
- <i>You are the only survivor of Krypton.</i>

74
00:15:02,683 --> 00:15:07,677
<i>Embedded in the crystals before you is</i>
<i>the total accumulation of all literature...</i>

75
00:15:07,843 --> 00:15:10,596
<i>...and scientific fact</i>
<i>from dozens of other worlds...</i>

76
00:15:10,763 --> 00:15:14,039
<i>...spanning the 28 known galaxies.</i>

77
00:15:14,523 --> 00:15:16,878
<i>There are questions to be asked.</i>

78
00:15:17,483 --> 00:15:19,075
<i>Here in this...</i>

79
00:15:19,243 --> 00:15:21,632
<i>This Fortress of Solitude...</i>

80
00:15:22,163 --> 00:15:25,519
<i>...we shall try to find</i>
<i>the answers together.</i>

81
00:15:25,683 --> 00:15:27,116
Can he see us?

82
00:15:27,843 --> 00:15:29,401
No, he's dead.

83
00:15:30,563 --> 00:15:31,837
<i>So, my son...</i>

84
00:15:35,283 --> 00:15:37,035
<i>...Kal-El...</i>

85
00:15:40,403 --> 00:15:42,359
<i>...speak.</i>

86
00:15:43,963 --> 00:15:45,840
Tell me everything...

87
00:15:46,003 --> 00:15:48,517
...starting with crystals.

88
00:18:38,123 --> 00:18:39,522
Hey, boy.

89
00:19:04,563 --> 00:19:06,474
- <i>on Tuesday, between support...</i>

90
00:19:06,643 --> 00:19:08,873
- <i>hindered the firefighting efforts</i>
<i>for all those...</i>

91
00:19:09,043 --> 00:19:13,514
<i>Police have finally arrived and it's</i>
<i>still complete mayhem down here.</i>

92
00:19:14,843 --> 00:19:17,118
<i>Fighting broke out in the</i>
<i>southernmost region...</i>

93
00:19:17,283 --> 00:19:19,592
<i>...with border fire</i>
<i>and small-arms attacks prevalent.</i>

94
00:19:19,763 --> 00:19:21,435
Don't worry, I buried it this morning.

95
00:19:21,603 --> 00:19:24,561
- <i>it was futile trying to force him</i>
<i>to testify before a grand jury.</i>

96
00:19:24,723 --> 00:19:26,156
Mom?

97
00:19:27,523 --> 00:19:29,434
Five years.

98
00:19:31,283 --> 00:19:34,514
If your father was alive,
he never would have let you go.

99
00:19:35,203 --> 00:19:36,716
I almost gave up hope.

100
00:19:36,883 --> 00:19:40,000
I just thought
I would never see you again.

101
00:19:40,723 --> 00:19:43,191
Oh, Clark.

102
00:19:50,163 --> 00:19:52,723
Did you find what you were looking for?

103
00:19:53,523 --> 00:19:57,072
I thought, hoped...

104
00:19:57,883 --> 00:19:59,601
...it might still be there.

105
00:20:00,283 --> 00:20:02,001
Your home?

106
00:20:04,403 --> 00:20:06,633
That place was a graveyard.

107
00:20:08,043 --> 00:20:09,442
I'm all that's left.

108
00:20:11,603 --> 00:20:14,993
Clark, the universe is a big place.

109
00:20:15,523 --> 00:20:17,673
And you don't know who's out there.

110
00:20:19,403 --> 00:20:21,758
And even if you are the last...

111
00:20:24,243 --> 00:20:25,995
...you're not alone.

112
00:20:30,643 --> 00:20:32,156
I know.

113
00:20:52,883 --> 00:20:53,998
- Sorry.
- Look out!

114
00:20:54,163 --> 00:20:55,357
Watch out, will you?

115
00:20:55,523 --> 00:20:56,956
- Excuse me.
- Sorry.

116
00:20:58,483 --> 00:20:59,757
Sorry.

117
00:21:01,203 --> 00:21:04,081
Great. Would you be careful?

118
00:21:05,043 --> 00:21:08,399
- Jimmy.
- Mr. Clark! I mean, Kent! Mr. Kent!

119
00:21:08,563 --> 00:21:10,554
Welcome back! Oh, my God!

120
00:21:10,723 --> 00:21:14,318
Hey, come... Wait right there.
I'll be right back.

121
00:21:23,403 --> 00:21:26,713
Oh, hey, sorry, guys,
I'm still looking for a place to live...

122
00:21:26,883 --> 00:21:28,555
...if you know of anything reasonable.

123
00:21:28,723 --> 00:21:32,238
Behind you, Mr. Kent.
I made it myself. It's a cake.

124
00:21:34,043 --> 00:21:35,476
Oh, it looks...

125
00:21:36,483 --> 00:21:37,632
...delicious.

126
00:21:37,803 --> 00:21:41,955
Olsen! Where are the photos
of that birthday-clown-massacre thing?

127
00:21:42,123 --> 00:21:44,591
I'm on it, chief. Hey, look who's back.

128
00:21:45,003 --> 00:21:46,322
- Kent?
- Hey, chief.

129
00:21:46,483 --> 00:21:48,872
- Thank you for giving me my job back.
- Don't thank me.

130
00:21:49,043 --> 00:21:50,317
Thank Norm Palmer for dying.

131
00:21:52,123 --> 00:21:54,000
It was his time.

132
00:21:55,243 --> 00:21:58,679
- Let's get you set up, huh?
- Olsen!

133
00:21:58,843 --> 00:22:00,037
Okay, so I gotta run...

134
00:22:00,203 --> 00:22:03,354
...but I will be back to check on you
in a sec, Mr. Kent.

135
00:22:03,523 --> 00:22:07,516
Oh, hey, do you know
where I can find Lois?

136
00:22:20,883 --> 00:22:23,158
<i>The timing of this</i>
<i>automated-ignition countdown...</i>

137
00:22:23,323 --> 00:22:25,393
<i>...is the most precarious part</i>
<i>of the launch.</i>

138
00:22:25,803 --> 00:22:27,122
<i>Lois Lane,</i> Daily Planet.

139
00:22:27,283 --> 00:22:30,400
<i>You also stated that the shuttle</i>
<i>will usher in a new era of travel...</i>

140
00:22:30,563 --> 00:22:33,475
<i>...enabling the average person</i>
<i>to afford transcontinental flights.</i>

141
00:22:33,643 --> 00:22:35,634
<i>But can you tell us the exact price...</i>

142
00:22:35,803 --> 00:22:38,271
<i>...an "average person"</i>
<i>will be expected to pay?</i>

143
00:22:38,483 --> 00:22:41,043
<i>The answer to that question</i>
<i>is in your press packet.</i>

144
00:22:41,203 --> 00:22:43,842
<i>The Earth is surrounded</i>
<i>by a blanket of air...</i>

145
00:22:44,003 --> 00:22:46,278
<i>...which we call the atmosphere.</i>

146
00:22:46,443 --> 00:22:49,879
<i>It reaches over...</i>

147
00:23:34,043 --> 00:23:36,716
Yeah. He looks just like his mom.

148
00:23:36,883 --> 00:23:40,717
Already takes after her too, especially
when it comes to getting into trouble.

149
00:23:40,883 --> 00:23:42,316
Mother?

150
00:23:44,083 --> 00:23:48,554
Oh, yeah, well, I guess you've been gone.
Fearless reporter Lois Lane is a mommy.

151
00:23:50,803 --> 00:23:53,954
Oh, you know, I'll just...
I'll take that. That's good.

152
00:23:54,123 --> 00:23:56,921
- Sorry.
- No. She's got plenty.

153
00:23:57,083 --> 00:23:58,960
- Wait, she's married?
- Yes.

154
00:23:59,443 --> 00:24:03,322
No. Not really. It's more like
a prolonged engagement.

155
00:24:03,483 --> 00:24:05,838
But don't ask Miss Lane
when they're tying the knot...

156
00:24:06,003 --> 00:24:09,393
...because she hates that question.

157
00:24:09,563 --> 00:24:13,841
- <i>like this follow the same stringent</i>
<i>safety guidelines set by NASA?</i>

158
00:24:14,003 --> 00:24:16,517
<i>Since this is a joint venture</i>
<i>with the Air Force...</i>

159
00:24:16,683 --> 00:24:20,039
You all right? You look like
you could use a drink.

160
00:24:22,363 --> 00:24:25,480
This place is so tacky.
Why are we back here?

161
00:24:25,643 --> 00:24:29,113
Kitty, while you were doing your nails
and ordering fur coats online...

162
00:24:29,283 --> 00:24:30,955
...I was busy unlocking the secrets...

163
00:24:31,123 --> 00:24:33,876
...of one of the most advanced
civilizations in the universe.

164
00:24:34,043 --> 00:24:35,237
Weren't there two of those?

165
00:24:35,403 --> 00:24:39,476
You see, unlike our clunky
earthbound forms of construction...

166
00:24:39,643 --> 00:24:41,998
...the technology on Krypton,
Superman's home world...

167
00:24:42,163 --> 00:24:44,472
...was based on manipulating
the growth of crystals.

168
00:24:44,643 --> 00:24:45,962
Sounds like hocus-pocus to me.

169
00:24:46,123 --> 00:24:49,718
Well, naturally, to the primitive mind,
any sufficiently advanced technology...

170
00:24:49,883 --> 00:24:51,919
...would be indistinguishable from magic.

171
00:24:52,083 --> 00:24:56,281
But imagine: cities, vehicles, weapons...

172
00:24:56,843 --> 00:24:58,401
...entire continents...

173
00:24:58,723 --> 00:25:01,362
...all grown.

174
00:25:08,723 --> 00:25:11,920
To think that one could create
a new world...

175
00:25:12,083 --> 00:25:14,961
...with such a simple little object.

176
00:25:16,603 --> 00:25:18,798
It's like a seed.

177
00:25:18,963 --> 00:25:21,113
And all it needs is water.

178
00:25:21,283 --> 00:25:22,682
Like...

179
00:25:23,443 --> 00:25:25,354
...Sea-Monkeys.

180
00:25:26,963 --> 00:25:29,158
Exactly, Kitty.

181
00:25:29,683 --> 00:25:31,275
Like Sea-Monkeys.

182
00:25:33,403 --> 00:25:37,794
Clark has been doing a little
soul-searching for the last couple years.

183
00:25:37,963 --> 00:25:39,874
- He saw Ilamas.
- Yeah?

184
00:25:40,043 --> 00:25:41,999
- Yeah.
- Must be tough coming back.

185
00:25:43,643 --> 00:25:45,713
- Coming back?
- To work.

186
00:25:46,603 --> 00:25:48,002
Yeah.

187
00:25:48,403 --> 00:25:50,871
Well, you know, things change.

188
00:25:51,043 --> 00:25:52,999
I mean, of course things change...

189
00:25:53,163 --> 00:25:58,795
...but sometimes things that you didn't
think would change could change.

190
00:25:59,243 --> 00:26:00,756
Take Lois.

191
00:26:00,923 --> 00:26:04,711
A woman like her,
I never thought she'd settle down.

192
00:26:05,163 --> 00:26:08,678
You know, if you ask me...
Because she'll never tell you this...

193
00:26:08,843 --> 00:26:13,519
...but if you ask me,
she's still in love with you-know-who.

194
00:26:21,523 --> 00:26:25,232
The original space shuttle
generated 7.5 million pounds of thrust...

195
00:26:25,403 --> 00:26:27,041
...just in the initial launch phase.

196
00:26:27,203 --> 00:26:31,754
But, by piggybacking
on this Boeing 777... Yes?

197
00:26:31,923 --> 00:26:33,879
If this launch is as pivotal as you claim...

198
00:26:34,043 --> 00:26:36,238
...why is it being covered
by one news network?

199
00:26:36,403 --> 00:26:39,475
Why don't we save those questions
for the post-launch briefing.

200
00:26:39,643 --> 00:26:41,201
How about that, Miss Lane?

201
00:26:41,363 --> 00:26:44,673
When we hit 40,000 feet,
the shuttle will detach, ascend...

202
00:26:44,843 --> 00:26:48,392
...and then fire the first of two propellant
systems, the liquid fuel boosters.

203
00:26:48,563 --> 00:26:50,519
When the shuttle
reaches the stratosphere...

204
00:26:50,683 --> 00:26:52,719
...the secondary
insertion booster will fire...

205
00:26:52,883 --> 00:26:56,114
...propelling the craft
at 4gs into the mesosphere.

206
00:26:59,803 --> 00:27:01,873
- Careful.
- I know.

207
00:27:02,683 --> 00:27:05,561
- Careful. Careful.
- I know.

208
00:27:31,683 --> 00:27:34,038
Wow, that's really something, Lex.

209
00:27:34,203 --> 00:27:36,398
Wait for it.

210
00:27:39,683 --> 00:27:42,322
Wow, that's really something, Lex.

211
00:27:44,683 --> 00:27:47,277
It's freaking <i>Gone With the Wind.</i>

212
00:27:47,923 --> 00:27:49,879
- Shut off the camera.
- But I'm getting it.

213
00:27:50,043 --> 00:27:51,999
I said, shut off the damn camera.

214
00:27:58,123 --> 00:27:59,761
I think I did something wrong.

215
00:27:59,923 --> 00:28:04,075
No. That wasn't you.

216
00:28:30,523 --> 00:28:34,038
<i>Ignition is at T minus one minute</i>
<i>and we are prepping for separation.</i>

217
00:28:34,203 --> 00:28:35,636
CDR., start the clock.

218
00:28:36,243 --> 00:28:38,473
<i>Three minutes and counting.</i>

219
00:28:38,643 --> 00:28:40,793
<i>Body signs normal. Crew is looking good.</i>

220
00:28:40,963 --> 00:28:42,555
Shuttle readouts are holding steady.

221
00:28:42,723 --> 00:28:44,873
- We're still a go for launch.
- <i>Roger.</i>

222
00:28:52,083 --> 00:28:54,836
- Houston, you copy?
- <i>Houston, do you copy?</i>

223
00:28:58,643 --> 00:28:59,632
Oh, God.

224
00:29:01,043 --> 00:29:02,715
<i>Electrical variance.</i>

225
00:29:06,363 --> 00:29:07,842
What the...?

226
00:29:14,443 --> 00:29:16,399
Please, there's nothing to worry about.

227
00:29:16,563 --> 00:29:20,636
It seems that we are experiencing
a slight power outage.

228
00:29:24,443 --> 00:29:27,753
- What did you do?
- It wasn't me. It just cycled back up.

229
00:29:29,243 --> 00:29:30,835
Genesis<i>, radio check from Houston.</i>

230
00:29:32,403 --> 00:29:34,792
There we have it.
We were experiencing a power outage.

231
00:29:37,123 --> 00:29:39,591
- Climbing to 40,000 feet.
- <i>Roger, 40,000 feet.</i>

232
00:29:50,643 --> 00:29:53,203
<i>And it's gone! A blazing fastball...</i>

233
00:30:13,803 --> 00:30:14,952
Is that it?

234
00:30:20,923 --> 00:30:23,153
I don't think so.

235
00:31:10,603 --> 00:31:12,958
<i>Dual engine failure,</i>
<i>but they're up and running again.</i>

236
00:31:13,123 --> 00:31:16,832
<i>Genesis,</i> I hate to say this, but it looks
like we're gonna have to scrub the launch.

237
00:31:17,003 --> 00:31:20,393
- Aborting booster ignition.
- Roger. Aborting booster ignition.

238
00:31:22,043 --> 00:31:25,160
Boosters are non-responsive.
We're still counting down for ignition.

