a cup of coffee sometime?

470
00:58:37,403 --> 00:58:39,837
- I know that's forward. Or a drink?
- Good night.

471
00:58:40,003 --> 00:58:41,595
Good night.

472
00:58:59,683 --> 00:59:01,241
It's like this on every channel.

473
00:59:01,403 --> 00:59:04,156
<i>He was in Manila at 10:55 P.M.</i>
<i>and then spotted...</i>

474
00:59:04,323 --> 00:59:07,918
- Hey, Kent, chief wants to see you.
- Oh, thanks.

475
00:59:08,083 --> 00:59:11,871
<i>But as this security footage</i>
<i>from a simple deli robbery proves...</i>

476
00:59:12,043 --> 00:59:15,035
<i>...there's really no feat too big</i>
<i>or too small for the Man of Steel.</i>

477
00:59:15,203 --> 00:59:18,320
<i>Reports are flooding in from Metropolis,</i>
<i>Houston, Gotham and as far...</i>

478
00:59:18,483 --> 00:59:21,122
<i>Satellites have proven</i>
<i>most ineffective at tracking him.</i>

479
00:59:21,283 --> 00:59:24,673
<i>He might literally be moving</i>
<i>near the speed of light.</i>

480
00:59:37,363 --> 00:59:40,116
- <i>Our map is illuminated with sightings...</i>
- Kent!

481
00:59:40,283 --> 00:59:43,195
- The chief is waiting.
<i>...on every continent, giving citizens...</i>

482
00:59:46,923 --> 00:59:50,472
These are iconic, and they were taken
by a 12-year-old with a camera phone.

483
00:59:50,643 --> 00:59:53,680
- What do you got, Olsen?
- I got those.

484
00:59:55,843 --> 00:59:57,515
- Look, in the sky, chief.
- It's a bird.

485
00:59:57,683 --> 00:59:59,196
- It's a plane.
- No, look, it's...

486
00:59:59,923 --> 01:00:01,072
You wanted to see me?

487
01:00:01,963 --> 01:00:03,601
Yeah, Kent, come on in. Sit down.

488
01:00:03,763 --> 01:00:06,641
I wanna talk a little strategy. Okay.

489
01:00:07,123 --> 01:00:09,683
First off, Lois, I don't understand
what you're doing...

490
01:00:09,843 --> 01:00:12,994
...sneaking around covering the blackout.
- It wasn't just a blackout.

491
01:00:13,163 --> 01:00:15,074
Cellphones, pagers,
automobiles, airplane...

492
01:00:15,243 --> 01:00:17,598
Every other paper in town
has got a female reporter...

493
01:00:17,763 --> 01:00:21,039
...a good-looking female reporter,
stashed on the roof covering Superman.

494
01:00:21,203 --> 01:00:24,718
- And you two are the ones with history.
- Chief, I've done Superman.

495
01:00:26,323 --> 01:00:28,279
Covered him. You know what I mean.

496
01:00:28,443 --> 01:00:30,513
Yeah, that makes you an expert.
Do him again.

497
01:00:30,683 --> 01:00:33,356
- There are a dozen other stories out there.
- Yeah? Name one.

498
01:00:33,523 --> 01:00:35,991
Well, there was a museum robbery
last night.

499
01:00:36,483 --> 01:00:39,793
Even Superman missed that one.
He was too busy saving this hooker.

500
01:00:39,963 --> 01:00:42,523
Why don't you guys
track down Lex Luthor?

501
01:00:43,203 --> 01:00:45,353
Well, no one's seen him
since his fifth appeal.

502
01:00:45,523 --> 01:00:47,593
He's got more history
with Superman than anyone.

503
01:00:47,763 --> 01:00:49,196
Maybe he's got something to say.

504
01:00:49,363 --> 01:00:52,958
- Luthor's yesterday's news.
- No, I like that idea.

505
01:00:53,883 --> 01:00:58,240
Perry, Lex Luthor is a career criminal
who nearly killed him, for God's sakes.

506
01:00:58,403 --> 01:01:00,553
Jimmy, how did Lex Luthor
get out of prison?

507
01:01:00,723 --> 01:01:04,557
Well, the appeals court called Superman
as a witness and he wasn't around.

508
01:01:05,243 --> 01:01:07,279
How much do you think
that pisses off Superman?

509
01:01:07,443 --> 01:01:09,001
- Give him to someone else.
- A lot.

510
01:01:09,163 --> 01:01:10,994
- A lot.
- Polly. Give him to Polly.

511
01:01:15,923 --> 01:01:17,402
Lois, Superman.

512
01:01:17,563 --> 01:01:19,679
- What about the blackout?
- Kent, blackout.

513
01:01:22,163 --> 01:01:24,393
Great. Thanks, chief.

514
01:01:27,403 --> 01:01:32,033
Lois, I'm sorry. I'd hate if this
damaged our relationship.

515
01:01:33,323 --> 01:01:34,392
Relationship?

516
01:01:35,123 --> 01:01:36,476
- Yeah.
- Hi, Mommy.

517
01:01:36,643 --> 01:01:38,440
- Hi, you.
- Hey, guys.

518
01:01:38,603 --> 01:01:42,232
He got an A in science, but a D in gym,
so we're doing something right.

519
01:01:42,403 --> 01:01:44,314
- Yeah, at least one of us is.
- What?

520
01:01:44,483 --> 01:01:47,202
It's Perry. He just shoved Superman
back into my life.

521
01:01:47,363 --> 01:01:50,196
Well, honey, I'm sure you can
find a way to interview Superman...

522
01:01:50,363 --> 01:01:52,274
...without bringing him
back into your life.

523
01:01:52,443 --> 01:01:56,561
<i>There's really no way around it, folks.</i>
<i>Superman is back in all of our lives.</i>

524
01:01:57,963 --> 01:01:59,681
<i>We're coming to you from Sydney...</i>

525
01:01:59,843 --> 01:02:03,472
<i>...where people have gathered</i>
<i>on these rooftops to scour the sky...</i>

526
01:02:03,643 --> 01:02:06,715
Okay, how about this?
We'll stay late. We'll get dinner.

527
01:02:06,883 --> 01:02:10,353
I'll help with Superman, and you and
Clark can work on the blackout together.

528
01:02:10,523 --> 01:02:13,356
- Is that all right with you, Clark?
- Swell.

529
01:02:36,283 --> 01:02:40,162
I was gonna pretend
the brakes were out.

530
01:02:40,323 --> 01:02:43,315
Pretend. Like we talked about.

531
01:02:43,483 --> 01:02:46,156
You didn't actually have to cut them!

532
01:02:46,323 --> 01:02:47,551
Of course I did.

533
01:02:47,723 --> 01:02:52,353
A man can always tell when a woman
is pretending, especially Superman.

534
01:02:57,043 --> 01:02:59,318
So did you get your rock?

535
01:03:00,643 --> 01:03:02,474
I did.

536
01:03:03,803 --> 01:03:07,682
<i>U.S. Coast Guard issuing a small-craft</i>
<i>advisory for the Metropolis ocean area.</i>

537
01:03:07,843 --> 01:03:09,595
<i>High-wind advisory is in effect...</i>

538
01:03:09,763 --> 01:03:12,516
<i>...ocean currents and tides</i>
<i>becoming increasingly dangerous.</i>

539
01:03:12,683 --> 01:03:15,755
<i>All warnings lasting</i>
<i>until later this evening.</i>

540
01:03:15,923 --> 01:03:17,117
<i>Security, security.</i>

541
01:03:17,283 --> 01:03:22,516
<i>This is U.S. Coast Guard issuing</i>
<i>a small-craft advisory for northeast seas.</i>

542
01:03:22,683 --> 01:03:26,961
<i>Winds reaching 50 miles per hour,</i>
<i>high tides in the morning.</i>

543
01:03:27,123 --> 01:03:28,875
<i>Waves reaching 20 to 30 feet.</i>

544
01:03:29,043 --> 01:03:32,877
<i>This warning is in effect for</i>
<i>all small crafts for the next four hours.</i>

545
01:03:56,003 --> 01:03:57,561
Weird. If these times are right...

546
01:03:57,723 --> 01:04:00,681
...the blackout spread
from a specific origin point.

547
01:04:00,843 --> 01:04:02,162
Where?

548
01:04:02,323 --> 01:04:04,041
I'm not sure yet.

549
01:04:04,723 --> 01:04:08,238
With the super-hearing, does he hear each
sound by itself or everything at once?

550
01:04:08,603 --> 01:04:09,797
<i>Both.</i>

551
01:04:09,963 --> 01:04:12,079
- <i>He's certainly taller than I thought.</i>
- <i>6'4".</i>

552
01:04:12,243 --> 01:04:15,838
I love that he can see through anything.
I'd have fun with that.

553
01:04:16,203 --> 01:04:17,841
<i>Anything but lead.</i>

554
01:04:20,963 --> 01:04:22,157
- I bet he's...
- 225 pounds...

555
01:04:22,323 --> 01:04:23,915
...faster than a speeding bullet...

556
01:04:24,083 --> 01:04:27,393
...draws his power from the sun,
invulnerable to anything but kryptonite...

557
01:04:27,563 --> 01:04:29,519
...and he never lies.
- Kryptonite?

558
01:04:29,683 --> 01:04:31,913
Radioactive pieces of his home world.

559
01:04:32,083 --> 01:04:34,199
It's deadly. To him.

560
01:04:38,603 --> 01:04:41,834
Lois, how tall would you say Clark is?

561
01:04:43,323 --> 01:04:45,234
<i>About 6'3", 6'4".</i>

562
01:04:45,403 --> 01:04:48,076
<i>About 200, 215 pounds?</i>

563
01:04:57,643 --> 01:05:01,477
Jimmy, Jason, let's go get these intrepid
reporters something to keep them going.

564
01:05:01,643 --> 01:05:03,440
- Burritos!
- Come here, canhead.

565
01:05:04,883 --> 01:05:08,671
We're going this way. Do they have
anything other than burritos?

566
01:05:09,523 --> 01:05:11,753
I think they have fries and burgers.

567
01:05:11,923 --> 01:05:14,312
So have you found a place to live yet?

568
01:05:14,483 --> 01:05:15,996
No. I'm still looking.

569
01:05:16,723 --> 01:05:19,112
You know, Lois, I wanted to ask you
about that artic...

570
01:05:19,283 --> 01:05:22,639
Hey, I'm gonna run downstairs
for some fresh air. Great!

571
01:05:35,843 --> 01:05:37,481
Thanks.

572
01:05:44,963 --> 01:05:47,602
- Let's talk when I get back.
- Sure.

573
01:06:38,923 --> 01:06:41,562
You know, you really
shouldn't smoke, Miss Lane.

574
01:06:44,723 --> 01:06:47,112
- Sorry. Didn't mean to startle you.
- I'm fine. Really.

575
01:06:49,163 --> 01:06:52,155
I just wasn't expecting you.

576
01:06:52,803 --> 01:06:54,316
With all the press on the plane...

577
01:06:54,483 --> 01:06:56,792
...I wasn't sure it was
the best time for us to talk.

578
01:06:56,963 --> 01:07:00,000
Well, there's no press around now.
Except for me, of course.

579
01:07:02,123 --> 01:07:04,478
I know people are asking questions
now that I'm back.

580
01:07:04,843 --> 01:07:08,233
I think it's only fair
that I answer those people.

581
01:07:09,843 --> 01:07:13,040
So you're here for an interview?

582
01:07:14,243 --> 01:07:15,232
Okay, then.

583
01:07:18,963 --> 01:07:20,874
- Where did I put that thing?
- Right pocket.

584
01:07:26,763 --> 01:07:29,357
Let's start with the big question.

585
01:07:29,523 --> 01:07:31,912
- Where'd you go?
- To Krypton.

586
01:07:32,083 --> 01:07:34,358
But you told me it was destroyed.
Ages ago.

587
01:07:34,523 --> 01:07:35,922
It was.

588
01:07:36,083 --> 01:07:38,358
But when astronomers
thought they found it...

589
01:07:39,763 --> 01:07:42,038
...I had to see for myself.

590
01:07:45,523 --> 01:07:49,198
Well, you're back, and everyone
seems to be pretty happy about it.

591
01:07:52,283 --> 01:07:53,682
Not everyone.

592
01:07:54,803 --> 01:07:57,112
- I read the article, Lois.
- So did a lot of people.

593
01:07:57,283 --> 01:08:00,116
- Tomorrow they're giving me the Pulitzer...
- Why did you write it?

594
01:08:01,723 --> 01:08:03,679
How could you leave us like that?

595
01:08:05,123 --> 01:08:07,432
I moved on. So did the rest of us.

596
01:08:07,923 --> 01:08:09,356
That's why I wrote it.

597
01:08:09,523 --> 01:08:12,196
The world doesn't need a savior.

598
01:08:12,603 --> 01:08:14,434
And neither do I.

599
01:08:28,963 --> 01:08:29,998
Lois.

600
01:08:31,643 --> 01:08:33,998
Will you come with me?

601
01:08:35,683 --> 01:08:37,196
Why?

602
01:08:37,563 --> 01:08:39,599
There's something I wanna show you.

603
01:08:45,603 --> 01:08:47,321
Please.

604
01:08:57,883 --> 01:08:59,953
I can't be gone long.

605
01:09:00,123 --> 01:09:01,954
You won't be.

606
01:09:13,843 --> 01:09:16,482
Clark said the reason you left
without saying goodbye...

607
01:09:16,643 --> 01:09:18,838
...is because it was
too unbearable for you.

608
01:09:19,003 --> 01:09:21,517
Personally, I think that's a load of crap.

609
01:09:22,083 --> 01:09:25,120
- Clark?
- He's just a guy I work with.

610
01:09:26,163 --> 01:09:28,199
Maybe Clark's right.

611
01:09:31,443 --> 01:09:33,479
You know, my...

612
01:09:33,643 --> 01:09:38,478
Richard, he's a pilot.
He takes me up all the time.

613
01:09:39,603 --> 01:09:41,514
Not like this.

614
01:09:55,763 --> 01:09:58,072
I forgot how warm you were.

615
01:10:27,443 --> 01:10:28,876
Listen.

616
01:10:29,723 --> 01:10:31,554
What do you hear?

617
01:10:32,243 --> 01:10:33,437
Nothing.

618
01:10:37,203 --> 01:10:38,875
I hear everything.

619
01:10:42,203 --> 01:10:44,717
You wrote that the world
doesn't need a savior...

620
01:10:46,003 --> 01:10:49,200
...but every day
I hear people crying for one.

621
01:11:01,523 --> 01:11:04,083
I'm sorry I left you, Lois.

622
01:11:07,803 --> 01:11:09,759
I'll take you back now.

623
01:13:17,443 --> 01:13:19,001
Richard's a good man.

624
01:13:22,283 --> 01:13:24,399
And you've been gone a long time.

625
01:13:26,963 --> 01:13:28,476
I know.

626
01:13:33,043 --> 01:13:34,317
I...

627
01:13:39,323 --> 01:13:41,234
So will I see you around?

628
01:13:42,203 --> 01:13:44,114
I'm always around.

629
01:13:45,363 --> 01:13:47,001
Good night, Lois.

630
01:14:05,203 --> 01:14:08,912
We're having beef, honey. Do you want
the tofu wrap or the veggie wrap?

631
01:14:12,680 --> 01:14:14,193
You all right?

632
01:14:15,960 --> 01:14:17,313
Where have you been?

